The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Friday, October 22, 2004 

 BRIEFS

 Kakdwip (South 24- Parganas), Oct. 21: Five persons, including Nepal?s joint secretary of health, were killed and six injured in a road accident today in South 24-Parganas.

 The victims were going in a Tata Sumo to visit the Kapil Muni temple at Ganga Sagar Island, said police superintendent S.. Gupta. The vehicle collided head-on with a truck at Kashinagar in Kakdwip, about 70 km from Calcutta, around 1 pm, he said.

 Bolpur: Two workers were charred to death when the crackers in a factory in Lubhpur, 240 km from Calcutta, exploded. The fire is said to have been touched off by carelessly thrown bidi ends and matchsticks. The bodies have been sent to the Bolpur subdivisional hospital for post mortem.

 Krishnagar (Nadia): Police have arrested 40 motor-van pullers last evening when they were demonstrating in front of the residence of police superintendent Benoy Chakraborty, demanding licences for their vehicles. The agitators pelted stones, injuring some policemen during the demonstration 85 km from Calcutta.

 Calcutta: Trinamul Congress chief Mamata Banerjee will move the Supreme Court against alleged large-scale rigging by CPM supporters in recent elections across the state. The Trinamul leader said the party has collected documents from various sources to substantiate the allegations.

 Panihati (North 24-Parganas): The state government has recently signed a memorandum of understanding with the Kerala-based Mata Amritanandamayi Trust for providing shelter to the poor. The trust and the Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority will jointly construct 200 flats for the poor at Panihati, according to the agreement. Each flat will cost Rs 60,000.

 Hooghly: A man wanted in connection with the murder of a CPM leader in April 2003 was beaten to death on Thursday morning. Nepal Das, 30, was entering his village in Khanakul police station area when residents of Chabbishpur village lynched him. Police personnel have been posted at the village to prevent the situation from getting out of control.




